CHAPTER 10\par
THE ASTEROID THAT WAS\par
Bigman had brought Conway and Henree to Ceres on Lucky's own ship, the \i Shooting Starr, \i0 and for that Lucky was grateful. It meant he could go out into space with it, feel its deck beneath his feet, hold its controls in his hands.\par
The \i Shooting Starr \i0 was a two-man cruiser, built this last year after Lucky's exploits among the farm boys of Mars. Its appearance was as deceptive as modern science could make it. It had almost the appearance of a space-yacht in its graceful lines, and its extreme length was not more than twice that of Hansen's little rowboat. No traveler in space, meeting the \i Shooting Starr, \i0 would have estimated it to be anything more than a rich man's plaything, speedy perhaps but thin-skinned and unequal to hard knocks. Certainly it would not have seemed the type of vessel to trust in the dangerous reaches of the asteroid belt.\par
An investigation of the interior of the vessel might have changed some of those notions, however. The gleaming hyperatomic motors were the equal of those on armored space-cruisers ten times the \i Shooting Starr's \i0 weight. Its energy reserve was tremendous and the capacity of its hysteretic shield was sufficient to stop the largest projectile that could be put out against it by any-\par
112 LUCKY STARR\par
thing short of a dreadnought. Offensively its limited mass prevented it from being first-class, but weight for weight it could outfight any ship.\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi432\qc * * *\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi432 It was no wonder that Bigman capered with delight once he had entered the air-lock and thrown off his space-suit.\par
"Space," Bigman said, "I'm glad to get off that other tub. What do we do with it?"\par
"I'll have them send up a ship from Ceres to scoop it . \i\'bb \i0 in.\par
Ceres was behind them, a hundred thousand miles away. In appearance it was about half the diameter of the Moon as seen from Earth.\par
Bigman said curiously, "How about letting me in on all this, Lucky? Why the sudden change of plans? I was heading out all by myself, the last I heard."\par
"There aren't any co-ordinates for you to head to," said Lucky. Grimly he told him the events of the last several hours.\par
Bigman whistled. "Then where are we going?"\par
"I'm not sure," said Lucky, "but we begin by aiming at the place where the hermit's rock ought to be now."\par
He studied the dials, and added, "And we leave here fast, too."\par
He \i meant \i0 fast. Acceleration on the \i Shooting Starr \i0 went high as velocity built up. Bigman and Lucky were pinned back to their diamagnetically cushioned chairs and the growing pressure spread evenly over their entire body surfaces. The oxygen concentration in the cabin was built up by the acceleration-sensitive air-purifier\par
THE ASTEROID THAT WAS 113\par
controls and allowed shallower breathing without oxygen starvation. The g-harness (g being the usual scientific symbol for acceleration) they both wore was light and did not hamper their movements, but under the stress of increasing velocity it stiffened and protected the bones, particularly the spine, from breaking. A nylotex-mesh girdle kept the abdominal viscera from undue harm.\par
In every respect the cabin accessories had been designed by experts at the Council of Science to allow of twenty to thirty per cent greater acceleration on the \i Shooting Starr \i0 than on even the most advanced vessels of the fleet.\par
Even on this occasion the acceleration, though high, was less than half of that of which the ship was capable.\par
When velocity leveled off, the \i Shooting Starr \i0 was five million miles from Ceres, and, if Lucky or Bigman had been interested in looking for it, they would have found it to have become, in appearance, merely a speck of light, dimmer than many of the stars.\par
Bigman said, "Say, Lucky, I've been wanting to ask you. Do you have your glimmer shield?"\par
Lucky nodded and Bigman looked grieved.\par
"Well, you big dumb ox," the little fellow said, "why in space didn't you take it with you when you went out pirate-hunting then?"\par
